n\n1. **start()** (raft.go:173-306): Main goroutine that:\n   - Ticks the Raft state machine periodically (heartbeat interval)\n   - Monitors Ready() channel for state changes\n\n2. **tick()** (raft.go:158-163): Called on each heartbeat interval, advances Raft's internal election timer\n\n3. **Leader Detection** (raft.go:185-197): When Ready() returns with rd.SoftState:\n   - Checks if `rd.SoftState.Lead` indicates a new leader\n   - Updates lead status via `updateLead(rd.SoftState.Lead)`\n   - Sets `islead` flag based on `rd.RaftState == raft.StateLeader`\n\n4. **Message Processing**:\n   - Leader: Sends messages immediately (line 240)\n   - Followers: Process messages after applying (line 297)\n\n### Failover & Re-election Mechanism\n\nFailover in Raft is automatic and consensus-driven:\n\n1. **Heartbeat Monitoring**: The leader sends heartbeats to all followers at regular intervals. Followers maintain an election timeout.\n\n2. **Timeout Detection**: When a follower doesn't receive a heartbeat within the election timeout:\n   - It becomes a candidate\n   - Increments its term\n   - Requests votes from other nodes\n\n3. **Leader Election**: A candidate becomes leader when:\n   - It receives votes from a majority of the cluster\n   - It has the most up-to-date log\n   - This guarantees only one leader per term\n\n4. **Failover Time**: Determined by election timeout (typically 150-300ms in etcd):\n   - Faster than Kubernetes lease-based election (~15s)\n   - Can tolerate network partitions better through quorum-based decisions\n   - Guarantees safety: split-brain is impossible (only one leader can be elected per term)\n\n### Key Differences\n\n1. **Consistency Model**:\n   - Kubernetes: Lease-based, relies on API server lock semantics, vulnerable to clock skew\n   - etcd: Consensus-based through Raft, guarantees strong consistency\n\n2. **Failure Detection**:\n   - Kubernetes: Time-based (lease expiration), takes 15+ seconds\n   - etcd: Heartbeat-based, takes 150-300ms\n\n3. **Split-brain Prevention**:\n   - Kubernetes: Not guaranteed (multiple leaders possible during network partitions)\n   - etcd: Prevented by Raft quorum requirement (only majority can elect leader)\n\n4. **Failover Mechanism**:\n   - Kubernetes: Implicit in lease renewal, candidates wait for lease expiration\n   - etcd: Explicit in Raft protocol, automatic election triggered by timeout\n\n5. **Usage Context**:\n   - Kubernetes: Used by controllers/operators for coordination\n   - etcd: Used for server-to-server leader election within the distributed system itself"
